Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js App Router project

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js application using the App Router architecture.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` package (v1.6.1) using npm
- Updated `package.json` to include the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with resolved dependencies

### 2. Analytics Component Integration
Modified: `src/app/layout.tsx`
- Imported `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag
- Placed the component after the existing `<Toaster />` component to ensure proper rendering order

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was added to the root layout file (`src/app/layout.tsx`) as this is an App Router project. The component was placed inside the `<body>` tag, which is the recommended approach for App Router projects to ensure:
- Analytics tracking is active across all pages
- The component loads with the application
- No impact on existing functionality or UI

## Verification Steps Completed

1. ✅ Build verification: Successfully ran `npm run build` - build completed without errors
2. ✅ Linting: Ran `npm run lint` - no linting errors introduced
3. ✅ Tests: Ran `npm run test` - all 258 tests passed (15 test files)
4. ✅ Dependencies: Lock file properly updated with new package

## Technical Decisions

- Used npm as the package manager (detected via existing package-lock.json)
- Followed App Router conventions by modifying the root layout
- Maintained existing code structure and formatting
- Preserved all existing imports and components
- Placed Analytics component at the end of the body to avoid interference with existing UI components

## Notes

The Analytics component will automatically track page views and web vitals when deployed to Vercel. No additional configuration is required for basic analytics functionality. The component is lightweight and won't impact page performance.
